RT--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Mitch always with the holier then thou UK bravado....since you didn't want to look up any statistics, I looked on that US Bureau of Justice Statistics, regarding US, england and wales.... here are some links:<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
For the victim surveys:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
U.S. surveys involve interviews with persons age 12 or older; English surveys, age 16 or older.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not sure exactly what affect this will have on the statistics, but clearly it would be a mistake to compare them directly without taking this into account, as has been done here. It would be nice to be able to obtain US statistics without the reports of those age 12-15, to have a better grounds for comparison. Also, I'd like to know whether the way in which the surveys were conducted is comparable in the two countries.<br>
<br>
More disturbingly:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Note that pre-1992 U.S. estimates for assault and burglary were adjusted to make them comparable to later year estimates.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
What does this mean ?!?! How have they been adjusted? Perhaps the unadjusted data would show similar trends in burglary and assault rates in the two countries.<br>
<br>
For both sets of data:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
assault was defined as aggravated assault in the U.S., and wounding in England<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I don't know what the legal difference between wounding and aggravated assault is. But it sounds like we aren't comparing apples and oranges here.<br>
<br>
And for the police reported data:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
murder was defined as murder or nonnegligent manslaughter in the United States, and murder/manslaughter or infanticide in England<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Could be wrong, but this sounds to me that to compare the results accurately, you need to add negligent manslaughter, and infanticide data to the US stats, or take it out of the UK ones. Thus relative to the UK rate, the US murder rate should be even higher. Or it could just be that these terms have different legal meanings in the two countries, and cover the same sorts of homocides.<br>
<br>
From this data, Aadan concludes:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Basicly says that the cops over there don't do shit, very reassuring...<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I assume Aadan's deduction is based on the fact that the police reports show a lower rate than the victim surveys. I see that for most of these crimes, US and UK crime rates are roughly equivalent (usually within 1.5-2 times each other). In BOTH countries, victim surveys show crime rates much higher than police records, by a much larger margin than the difference between the two countries (typically 3-4 times). So any reflection on one country's police would reasonably also apply to the other. I'm curious as to how the victims are found and surveys conducted for all these crime which aren't in police reports.<br>
<br>
The one major difference between the countries that I see is that with relatively similar rates for the other crimes, the murder and rape rates are much higher in the US than the UK (police reports only. For some reason there's no surveys of murder victims).<br>
<br>
Aadan also wrote:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Computer games don't affect kids. I mean if Pacman affected our generation as kids, we'd all run around in a darkened room munching pills and listening to repetitive music.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Which just goes to show that we don't think completely differently. Was the first thing I thought of posting when reading the video game comments.<br>
